{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17608875","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17608875"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:39:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:39:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16052"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16052","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16052"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.07,0.45,0.17,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8743"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63703"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8743","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8743"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16052"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49142"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"8124"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20907"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20908"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63703","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63703"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Australian pregnancy drug categorisation system includes a category described as: \u0027Drugs which, owing to their pharmacological effects, have caused or may be suspected of causing harmful effects on the human fetus or neonate without causing malformations. These effects may be reversible.\u0027\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following categories in the Australian pregnancy drug categorisation system is being described?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Category B2","Category B3","Category C","Category D","Category X"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe description provided matches \u003Cstrong\u003ECategory C\u003C/strong\u003E in the Australian pregnancy drug categorisation system. This category includes drugs that may have harmful effects on the fetus or neonate due to their pharmacological action, but do not cause structural malformations. Many commonly prescribed antidepressants, including selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs), fall into this category.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECategory B2\u003C/strong\u003E drugs have been taken by only a limited number of pregnant women, with no evidence of increased harm to the fetus. Animal studies are inadequate or lacking, but available data shows no evidence of fetal harm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECategory B3\u003C/strong\u003E drugs have been taken by only a limited number of pregnant women, with no evidence of increased harm to the fetus. Animal studies have shown evidence of fetal harm, but the significance in humans is uncertain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECategory D\u003C/strong\u003E drugs have caused, or are suspected to have caused, an increased incidence of human fetal malformations or irreversible damage. These drugs may also have adverse pharmacological effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECategory X\u003C/strong\u003E drugs have such a high risk of causing permanent damage to the fetus that they should not be used in pregnancy or when there is a possibility of pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that the pregnancy category system should not be used in isolation when making clinical decisions about medication use in pregnancy. Individual risk-benefit assessment, considering factors such as disease severity and alternative treatments, is essential.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Category C drugs may cause harmful effects on the human fetus or neonate without causing malformations, and these effects may be reversible.","The Australian pregnancy drug categorisation system helps guide medication safety in pregnancy, but should not be used in isolation for clinical decision-making.","Many commonly prescribed antidepressants are Category C medications in pregnancy."],"references":["Australian Government. Australian categorisation system for prescribing medicines in pregnancy. tga.gov.au. Available from: https://www.tga.gov.au/australian-categorisation-system-prescribing-medicines-pregnancy","B\u00e1nhidy F, Lowry RB, Czeizel AE. Risk and benefit of drug use during pregnancy. Int J Med Sci. 2005;2(3):100-6. doi: 10.7150/ijms.2.100. Epub 2005 Jul 1. PMID: 16007261; PMCID: PMC1168874.","Australian Government. Prescribing medicines in pregnancy database tga.gov.au. Available from: https://www.tga.gov.au/products/medicines/find-information-about-medicine/prescribing-medicines-pregnancy-database"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49142"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16052"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49142","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49142"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-22T11:18:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-22T11:20:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8743"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63703"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"